record_data.record_plain_text: 1. Availability: Seller makes electric energy, capacity and ancillary services available as a power marketer under this Rate Schedule for wholesale sales to any purchaser with whom Seller has contracted. 2. Applicability: This Rate Schedule is applicable to all sales of electric energy, capacity and ancillary services by Seller not otherwise subject to a particular Rate Schedule of Seller. 3. Rates: All sales shall be made at the rates established between Seller and the purchaser. 4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between Seller and the purchaser. 5. Ancillary Services: Seller will make available to any purchaser with whom it has contracted, the ancillary services listed in this Paragraph. a. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. b. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include l0-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, l0-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. c. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. d. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. e. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. ("MISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. f. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. ("SPP") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. g. Third-Party Ancillary Services: Seller Offers Regulation and Frequency Response Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation and Frequency Response Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 6. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff. 7. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 1 seller in the Northeast, Southeast, Central, Southwest, and Northwest regions and a Category 2 seller in the Southwest Power Pool region, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a). 8. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Seller has received waiver of: Subparts B and C of Part 35, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16. Seller has also received waiver of: Part 41, Part 101, and Part 141 with the exception of 18 C.F.R. 141.14 and 141.15. Seller has also received blanket approval under Part 34. (See Roosevelt Wind Project, LLC, Docket No. ER15-2130-000 (August 26, 2015) (unpublished letter order).) 9. Effective Date: This Tariff is effective on the date specified by the Commission.

Multiple Counterparts. 45 13.17 Memorandum. 45 Attachments: Exhibit A-1 - Shared Real Property Documents Exhibit A-2 - Shared Premises Map Exhibit A-3 - Gen Tie Line Description and Common Physical Facilities Exhibit B - Form of Assignment and Assumption Agreement Exhibit C - Proportionate Share of the Owners Exhibit D - Permitted Liens Exhibit E - Form of Transmission and Road Access Easement Agreement Schedule 2.3(b) -- Anticipated Costs and Expenses of Common Physical Facilities COTENANCY AND COMMON FACILITIES AGREEMENT This FIRST AMENDED AND RESTATED COTENANCY AND COMMON FACILITIES AGREEMENT (the "Agreement") is made and entered into as of December 21, 2015 (the "Execution Date") by and between ROOSEVELT WIND PROJECT, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Roosevelt"), and MILO WIND PROJECT, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Milo"). Each of Roosevelt and Milo is sometimes referred to herein individually as an "Owner" or a "Party" and collectively as the "Owners" or the "Parties." RECITALS A. Roosevelt is developing and will own and operate a wind-powered electric generation facility in Roosevelt County, New Mexico, with a Nameplate Capacity of up to 250 MW (the "Roosevelt Project"). The Roosevelt Project includes, among other things, the siting, construction and operation of a substation station for use in gathering the production from the Roosevelt Project (the "Roosevelt Substation Station"). The Roosevelt Substation Station will be designed to accommodate 345kV output from the Roosevelt Project. B. Milo is developing and will own and operate a wind-powered electric generation facility adjacent to the Roosevelt Project in Roosevelt County, New Mexico, with a Nameplate Capacity of up to 49.65 MW (the "Milo Project"). The Milo Project includes, among other things, the siting, construction and operation of a substation station for use in gathering the production from the Milo Project (the "Milo Substation Station"). The Milo Substation Station will be designed to accommodate 345kV output from the Milo Project. C. Each of the Owners expects to transmit electric energy generated from their respective Projects to the point of interconnection under the Interconnection Agreement and the Owners intend (i) the Interconnection Company will hold the Interconnection Agreement for the benefit of the Owners with respect to their separate Projects and (ii) each Owner will be bound by, and comply with, the terms of the Interconnection Agreement as a member of the Interconnection Company. D. To avoid the costly duplication of facilities necessary to transmit the output of their respective Projects to the point of interconnection under the Interconnection Agreement the Owners are jointly developing and intend to share the costs and ownership of a generation-intertie transmission line and related facilities (the "Gen-Tie Line"). The Gen-Tie Line, together with all of the Common Facilities, will be shared by the Owners. D. Pursuant to (i) the Shared Real Property Documents (defined herein) and (ii) those certain partial assignment and assumption or other agreements which may, in the future, be entered into by and between the Owners, each Owner holds or will hold its Proportionate Share as tenants-in-common in certain assets, including certain land, easements, rights-of-way and other real property interests, facilities, permits, agreements and other developmental assets, which assets shall be used by the Owners upon which the Gen-Tie Line will be constructed and accessed (the "Transmission Route"). In furtherance thereof, the Owners wish to set forth certain of their rights and responsibilities in respect of the development, construction and operation of the Common Facilities necessary for the Projects. E. The Parties entered into that certain Cotenancy and Common Facilities Agreement dated September 24, 2015 (the "Prior Agreement") and now wish to amend and restate that agreement. As of the Effective Date, each Owner is (i) the owner, as a tenant-in-common, of certain easement and access rights across the lands necessary for the Common Facilities, and (ii) required to bear its Proportionate Share of expenses, in accordance with this Agreement. AGREEMENT NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing and of the mutual covenants and agreements contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt of which is hereby acknowledged, the Owners, and each of them, hereby agree as follows: ARTICLE 1 CONSTRUCTION 1.1 Construction. (b) The terms "include", "includes" and "including", as used herein, are without limitation. The Recitals and Exhibits form an integral part of this Agreement. 1.2 Definitions. "Environment" means soil, land surface or subsurface strata, surface waters (including navigable waters and ocean waters), groundwater, drinking water supply, stream sediments, ambient air (including indoor air), plant and animal life, and any other environmental medium or natural resource related to either Project. "Environmental Law" means any legal requirement or Applicable Law pertaining to the quality of, protection, clean-up, Remediation or damage of or to the Environment, including, without limitation, the following Laws as the same may be from time to time amended: the Clean Air Act, as amended, 42 U.S.C. 7401, et seq.; the Clean Water Act, 33 U.S.C. 1251, et seq.; the Resource, Conservation and Recovery Act, 42 U.S.C. 6901, et seq.; the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation and Liability Act, 42 U.S.C. 9601, et seq.; the Safe Drinking Water Act, 42 U.S.C. 300f, et seq.; the Toxic Substances Control Act, 15 U.S.C. 2601, et seq.; the Federal Water Pollution Control Act, 33 U.S.C. 1251 et seq.; the Rivers and Harbors Act, 33 U.S.C. 401, et seq.; the Transportation Safety Act of 1974, 49 U.S.C. 1801 et seq.; the Endangered Species Act, 16 U.S.C. 1531, et seq.; the National Environmental Policy Act, 42 USC 4321 et seq.; the National Historic Preservation Act, 16 U.S.C 470 et seq.; Federal Land Policy and Management Act, 43 U.S.C. 1701 et seq; the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act, 42 U.S.C. 6901 et seq.; the Hazardous Materials Transportation Act, 49 U.S.C. 5101 et seq.; the Bald and Golden Eagle Protection Act, 16 U.S.C. 668 et seq.); and the Migratory Bird Treaty Act, 16 U.S.C. 703 et seq. "GDPIPD" means the Gross Domestic Product Implicit Price Deflator, as published by the Department of Commerce: Bureau of Economic Analysis immediately preceding the applicable date of adjustment, any successor index, or such other index as mutually agreed upon between the Owners. "Gen-Tie Line" has the meaning set forth in the recitals and as more specifically described on Exhibit A-3 attached to and made a part of this Agreement. "Permits" means any franchise, permit, authorization, license, approval or similar Order of or from any Governmental Authority necessary from time to time for the performance of the relevant work. For the avoidance of doubt, the Project Controlled Assets shall exclude any of the Common Facilities. "Projects" means, collectively, the Roosevelt Project and the Milo Project. "Proportionate Share" means, for each Owner, a share initially equal to the ratio of the Maximum Interconnection Capacity for such Owner's Project to the total interconnection capacity of the Common Facilities, which interest will be expressed as a percentage, and will be calculated by dividing (a) the Maximum Interconnection Capacity for such Owner's Project by (b) the total interconnection capacity of the Common Facilities. Each Owner's initial Proportionate Share is set forth in Exhibit C. Each Owner's Proportionate Share shall be adjusted based on the actual installed Nameplate Capacity of their respective projects after completion of construction of both the Roosevelt Project and the Milo Project. "Prudent Industry Practice" means those practices, methods, acts and standards, as changed from time to time, that (i) when engaged in, are commonly used in prudent engineering, contracting and operations to design, construct and operate equipment and facilities similar to the Common Facilities lawfully and with safety, reliability, efficiency, expedition and economy, or (ii) in the exercise of reasonable judgment considering the facts known when engaged in, could have been expected to achieve the desired result consistent with Applicable Law, safety, reliability, efficiency, expedition and economy. Prudent Industry Practice is not limited to the optimum practices, methods, acts or standards, but includes a spectrum of possible practices, methods, acts or standards. In determining which practices, methods and acts constitute Prudent Industry Practice, due regard shall be given to, among other things, manufacturers' warranties, contractual obligations, the requirements or guidance of Applicable Law, Governmental Authorities and the Transmission Provider, and the requirements of insurers, but in no event shall Prudent Industry Practice be interpreted to require any practice, method or act that violates Applicable Law. (vii) All costs, fees, damages and expenses to be paid in connection with decommissioning and removal of the Common Facilities and restoration of the underlying real property; (viii) All costs, fees and expenses to be paid in connection with the acquisition of the land interests contemplated by the Shared Real Property Documents, including any transfer premiums, reimbursements or fees paid to developers; and (xi) All reasonable consultant, expert and attorneys' costs, expenses and fees incurred in connection with the above or with respect to any necessary or beneficial regulatory filings or proceedings concerning the Common Facilities. "Shared Licenses and Permits" means, collectively, the governmental licenses, permits, approvals and authorizations, whether federal, state or local, including Environmental Permits, if any, necessary for and relating to the Common Physical Facilities, in which each Owner owns its Proportionate Share. "Shared Premises" means the portion of real property shared by the Owners in connection with this Agreement pursuant to the Shared Real Property Documents and as more particularly described on Exhibit A-1 hereto. "Shared Project Agreements" means, collectively, the Maintenance Agreement and all other agreements entered into by or on behalf of the Owners relating to the construction, maintenance and/or operation of the Common Physical Facilities. For the avoidance of doubt, the Shared Project Agreements shall exclude the Interconnection Agreement and any agreements entered into by an Owner or its Affiliates with respect to such Owner's respective Project. "Shared Real Property Documents" means those documents described in Exhibit A-1 hereto. For the avoidance of doubt, the Shared Real Property Documents shall exclude any easements, option agreements, leases, subordination agreements and other real property agreements entered into by an Owner or its Affiliates solely with respect to such Owner's or its Affiliates' respective Project. "Taking" has the meaning set forth in Section 13.13. "TO/TOP Expenses" has the meaning set forth in Section 4.8(a). "Transferring Party" has the meaning set forth in Section 8.1. "Transmission Owner" means the Southwestern Public Service Company. "Transmission Route" has the meaning set forth in recitals. "Transmission Service Provider" or "TSP" mean the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. "SPP Protocols" means the documents adopted by the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. ("SPP"), including exhibits or attachments referenced therein that contain the scheduling, operating, planning, reliability and settlement policies, rules, guidelines (including operating guides), procedures, standards and criteria of the Southwest Power Pool, Inc., as such documents may be amended from time to time. "SPS Switching Station" means the Southwestern Public Service Company owned and operated Switching Station on the Eddy County to Tolk 345 kV transmission line (including the revenue meter) to which the Common Physical Facilities will be interconnected in accordance with the Interconnection Agreement. "Withdrawal Costs" has the meaning given in Section 13.4. ARTICLE 2 JOINT OWNERSHIP AND USE OF COMMON FACILITIES 2.1 Owners' Intent. (a) Each Owner shall have an undivided ownership interest, as tenants-in-common, in all of the Common Facilities equal to such Owner's Proportionate Share upon the Effective Date, and has executed this Agreement in order to provide for the acquisition, ownership, development, operation and maintenance of the Common Facilities. The Owners hereby declare that (i) the Common Facilities shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of the Projects and related transmission of electricity generated by or on behalf of the Owners from the Projects to the applicable points of interconnection and (ii) each Owner has the right to utilize the Common Facilities only up to the Owner's Maximum Interconnection Capacity for its Project. (b) Upon the Effective Date, each Owner shall have an undivided interest, as tenants-in-common, in all of the Real Property Rights granted by the Shared Real Property Documents. (c) The Owners acknowledge and agree that each Owner will use no more than its Proportionate Share of the Common Facilities to transmit electrical energy from its Project and that (i) neither Owner will provide any interconnection or transmission services to the other Owner under this Agreement, (ii) neither Owner will pay a fee or make any other payment to the other Owner for the transmission of the first Owner's electricity, and (iii) neither Owner shall have any obligation to the other Owner to provide any interconnection or related rights with a transmission provider. (d) After the Effective Date, as soon as commercially practicable, Roosevelt and Milo shall execute and deliver documentation reasonably necessary to record and effect the transfers contemplated herein, including, without limitation, an Assignment and Assumption Agreement for an undivided interest in all Common Facilities, in each case in substantially the form attached to this Agreement as Exhibit B. 2.2 Ownership of Real Property Rights. (a) The Parties acknowledge that stand alone easements ("Easements"), deeds, leases, licenses and other real property agreements ("Real Property Rights") have been obtained for the Common Physical Facilities over and across the Transmission Route pursuant to the Shared Real Property Documents. If any additional Easements are determined to be required for the Transmission Route, such Easements will be in substantially the form of Transmission and Road Access Easement attached hereto as Exhibit E and incorporated herein by this reference. The applicable Parties shall diligently work and use commercially reasonable efforts to acquire such additional Real Property Rights as soon as commercially reasonable. The Parties shall, and shall cause their Affiliates to, reasonably cooperate with each other to obtain any consents or approvals with respect to the Transmission Route that may be required from third parties. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Parties acknowledge and agree that acquisition of any additional Real Property Rights requires cooperation of third parties not controlled by the Parties, and as such, no failure to obtain any additional Real Property Rights as described herein shall constitute or be deemed to be a default hereunder by any Party. (b) All verifiable out-of-pocket costs, fees and expenses (including reasonable attorneys' fees and expenses) of acquiring the Real Property Rights and obtaining title insurance for the Real Property Rights shall be shared by the Parties in accordance with the cost-sharing provisions related to the Common Physical Facilities contained in Section 3.4 of this Agreement. (c) Any internal overhead costs incurred by an Owner in relation to obtaining the Real Property Rights including travel costs related thereto, shall be paid by that Owner. (d) Any rental, royalty or lease payments required for the Real Property Rights pursuant to the Shared Real Property Documents shall be Shared Expenses. (e) Notwithstanding any provision of the Real Property Rights that would allow termination of such Real Property Rights, each Owner shall keep and maintain such Real Property Rights in full force and effect for so long as this Agreement is in force and effect. Each Owner shall have the right, but not the obligation, to cure in full all defaults by the other Owners, as a grantee under the Real Property Rights, in the performance of any covenant, condition or agreement contained in the Real Property Rights. The defaulting Owner shall, upon demand, reimburse the non-defaulting Owner for all reasonable and verifiable out-of-pocket costs, fees and expenses (including reasonable attorneys' fees and expenses) incurred by the non-defaulting Owner in curing any such default by the defaulting Owner under the Real Property Rights. Upon receipt by any Owner of a notice of default under the Real Property Rights, the Owner receiving such notice shall immediately deliver a copy thereof to the other Owner and any Lender. 2.3 Construction; Joint Ownership; and Use of Common Facilities. (a) Roosevelt shall initially construct the Common Physical Facilities in a manner that accommodates the Maximum Interconnection Capacity for both the Roosevelt and Milo Projects (i.e., 299.65 MW), including without limitation constructing the point of demarcation for each of the Roosevelt and Milo Projects on the shared side of the 345kV disconnect switches at the point of attachment where the bus jumpers connect with the disconnect switches (collectively, the "Common Switchyard"). Roosevelt shall also obtain the Shared Licenses and Permits in a manner that accommodates the Maximum Interconnection Capacity for both the Roosevelt and Milo Projects (i.e., 299.65 MW). (b) Roosevelt shall be reimbursed by Milo for Milo's Proportionate Share of the costs and expenses Roosevelt incurs for the acquisition of the Real Property Rights and the design, development and construction of the Common Physical Facilities. The assets constituting the Common Physical Facilities and the anticipated costs and expenses associated with the initial construction of the Common Physical Facilities as of the Execution Date are more particularly described in Schedule 2.3(b) attached to this Agreement. (c) Roosevelt shall cause the Common Physical Facilities to be constructed, in a good and workmanlike manner, and in accordance with all Applicable Laws, Permits and applicable real property rights, and shall use commercially reasonable efforts to complete such construction in a timely manner. (d) The Parties acknowledge that all planning, construction and installation of interconnection and transmission facilities required for the Projects, including any upgrades and additional design or operational components as may be necessary with respect to the Common Physical Facilities and the facilities of a Project, shall be constructed pursuant to the Interconnection Agreement and Prudent Industry Practice and in a manner that is consistent with the mutually agreed plans and specifications for the Common Physical and the facilities of a Project. (e) Each Owner shall install and maintain primary and backup revenue grade metering devices as originally installed, or is reasonably acceptable to the Common Facilities Manager and the other owner, and the TSP or the Transmission Owner; and shall permit the Common Facilities Manager to read the results of such metering device upon reasonable prior notice from the Common Facilities Manager. The metering devices for each Project shall be maintained in the original locations, and shall not be moved or altered. The Owners agree that the Common Facilities Manager shall operate under and adhere to the Metering and Billing Agreement with regard to generating resource meter splitting. All revenue metering shall be calculated using the Trimark computers originally installed and programed per the Metering and Billing Agreement, and none of the metering shall be altered, in any way, without all parties being notified and in agreement first; all work may be reviewed by the other parties. (f) The Owners acknowledge and agree that the TSP or Transmission Owner may require the use of the Common Facilities for the co-location of certain control, metering and monitoring equipment servicing and connecting the Projects. The Parties agree to cooperate in good faith to provide the TSP or Transmission Owner with rights to use the Common Facilities to so service the Projects. (g) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein, any additional facilities, real property rights, operational components, upgrades, modifications, improvements or other option or construction rights which are commercially and reasonably necessary for the Common Facilities that are constructed or acquired by an Owner, or any Affiliate thereof, shall be: (i) procured by such Owner (not any Affiliate thereof) for and on behalf of itself and the other Owners, (ii) added as Common Facilities hereunder and deemed incorporated into, and governed by, the terms hereof and (iii) owned by the Owners in accordance with their respective Proportionate Shares. At the request of either Owner, the Owners shall execute such documents as are reasonably necessary to document such ownership as soon as commercially practicable after the receipt of a request for the same. (h) To the extent that an Owner or the Common Facilities Manager has the right to be reimbursed or otherwise paid costs, fees, expenses or losses under this Agreement, such Person shall use commercially reasonable efforts to minimize such cost, fees, expenses or losses. (i) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein, each Owner shall be solely responsible for the payment of any and all grid interconnection or other charges, registration costs, or other fees or costs related to the delivery of electrical energy generated by its Project to the Interconnection Point, including but not limited to, any such charges, fees or costs for scheduling, imbalance, or ancillary services; provided, however, that it is expressly understood and agreed that each Owner shall not request or receive any such services listed in this subjection (j) from any other Owner. (j) Each Owner shall promptly take such action (including, but not limited to, the execution, acknowledgment, delivery and recordation of separate deeds, assignments, bills of sale, and other documents and instruments) as may reasonably be requested by any other Owner to effect, evidence or vest each Owner's respective ownership interest in the Common Facilities or any portion thereof, or to evidence the transfer by such other Owner of any of its ownership interest in the Common Facilities within twenty-one (21) Business Days after the receipt of a request for the same. 2.4 Priority of Use. (a) In the event the Common Facilities Manager becomes aware of an equipment failure or an unanticipated event that requires the use of the Common Physical Facilities to be curtailed to protect the Common Physical Facilities, either Project, or human life, the Common Facilities Manager shall immediately notify each Owner or its designated scheduling agent. The Owners agree to cooperate (either directly or through their respective scheduling agents) to curtail their Projects in response to such unanticipated event. During such curtailment Roosevelt shall have priority use of the Common Physical Facilities until the termination of that certain Wind Energy Purchase Agreement between Roosevelt and Transmission Owner dated as of July 1, 2013. (b) To the extent any such curtailment or disconnection is directly caused by an act or omission of an Owner constituting negligence or willful misconduct or the breach by an Owner of this Agreement, then, notwithstanding subsection (a) above, (i) such Owner's Project shall be the first Project to be curtailed or disconnected and, subject to the last sentence of this subsection (b), the last Project to be permitted to use the Common Facilities following any such curtailment or disconnection, and (ii) such Owner shall be solely responsible for any and all lost revenues, costs and/or expenses (including the cash value of any lost federal production tax credits, grossed-up based on the actual combined state and federal income tax rate applicable to such Owner) incurred by the other Owner for any curtailment of some or all of the energy production attributable to such act, omission or breach. Such Owner's Project shall not be permitted to use the Common Facilities again unless and until the Common Facilities Manager determines that the deficiencies have been corrected, or the Owners otherwise agree. 2.5 Interconnection and Upgrades to Common Facilities. (a) No Owner shall interconnect any Project to the Common Physical Facilities to the extent such Project has a Nameplate Capacity in excess of such Project's Maximum Interconnection Capacity. To the extent that conditions exist that could result in an Owner delivering energy from its respective Project to its respective Project meter in excess of such Project's Maximum Interconnection Capacity and if such excess generation causes such Owner to be in noncompliance with the Interconnection Agreement and/or interferes with the other Owner's rights to utilize its Proportionate Share in the Common Facilities, then such Owner shall curtail the operation of its Project so as not to exceed its applicable amount. (b) If an Owner proposes any upgrades, additional design or operational components, modifications or improvements to the Common Physical Facilities the Owners shall review each proposal in good faith. If the Owners (or any of them) determine that any such proposal shall not have a material adverse effect on the Common Physical Facilities or on the Projects, the Owners shall allow the incorporation of such proposals into the Common Physical Facilities. Unless otherwise agreed by the other Owner in writing and subject to the other terms of this Agreement, the proposing Owner shall be solely responsible for: (i) the construction and the costs of any such upgrades, additional design or operational components, modifications or improvements (including, without limitation, the costs thereof for engineering, permitting, construction and interconnection) and the reasonable cost of any third party experts retained to study or review any such upgrades, additional design or operational components, modifications or improvements and (ii) any costs, expenses or revenue loss incurred (including the cash value of any lost federal production tax credits, grossed up based on the actual combined state and federal income tax rate applicable to such Owner) by any other Owner owning a Project then existing in connection with the construction, installation, startup, testing and/or interconnection of any such upgrades, additional design or operational components, modifications or improvements (including any penalties imposed on the other Owner or damages payable to a power purchaser, the TSP, or the other Owner). The proposing Owner shall reimburse any other Owner for any such costs, expenses and/or revenue losses within five (5) Business Days after the receipt of an invoice for the same. The costs and expenses of operating and maintaining any such upgrades, additional design or operational components, modifications and improvements shall be Shared Expenses and paid in accordance with Section 3.4. (c) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein, any such additional upgrades, additional design or operational components, modifications or improvements to the existing Common Facilities that are constructed or acquired pursuant to this Section shall be: (i) procured by the applicable Owner for and on behalf of itself and the other Owner, (ii) added as Common Facilities hereunder and deemed incorporated into, and governed by, the terms hereof and (iii) owned by the Owners in accordance with their then-applicable respective Proportionate Shares. At the request of either Owner, the Owners shall execute such documents as are necessary to document and record such ownership within twenty-one (21) Business Days after the receipt of a request for the same. 2.6 Rights to Electricity. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein, all electricity transmitted on, over and/or through the Common Facilities, as well as any proceeds, income or revenue related thereto, shall belong to each Owner in an amount equal to the energy transmitted into the Common Facilities from such Owner's Project, as adjusted for line losses in accordance with Section 3.4. 2.7 Scheduling. The Owners shall, as necessary, develop a protocol with respect to scheduling of energy deliveries under the respective power purchase agreements relating to each Project (if any) and in accordance with SPP Protocols. Each Owner shall bear any and all costs attributable to scheduling of energy from its Project. ARTICLE 3 OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF COMMON FACILITIES 3.1 Operation and Maintenance of the Common Facilities. Each Owner shall pay its then-applicable Proportionate Share of all future costs of operating and maintaining the Common Facilities in accordance herewith, as such costs are established and approved by the Common Facilities Manager, subject to each Owner's rights of approval and disapproval as set forth in Article 4. 3.2 Removal of Property. Each Owner shall have the express right, at any time and in its sole discretion, to remove and/or replace any part of its Project and all other property owned by such Owner, to the extent not jointly owned by the Owners. If removal or replacement of any of such property will materially affect in an adverse way the safety or operation of any of the Common Facilities, the Owner contemplating the removal or replacement shall consult with and obtain the consent of the other Owner before conducting the contemplated removal or replacement, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed, and subject to compliance with reasonable requirements of the consenting Owner in connection with the performance of such removal or replacement work to safeguard persons or property or minimize interference with operations. 3.3 Rights to Common Facilities. Each Owner retains the right to hold and utilize its then-applicable Proportionate Share of the Common Facilities to (a) connect its Project to the Common Facilities up to its respective Proportionate Share and (b) deliver or receive electrical energy corresponding to such Proportionate Share in accordance with the terms of this Agreement. 3.4 Shared Expenses and Line Losses. (a) Each Owner shall be obligated to pay all Shared Expenses in proportion to such Owner's then-applicable Proportionate Share. The Common Facilities Manager, as authorized agent for each Owner, shall administer the collection and payment of the Shared Expenses, either through a monthly invoice to an individual Owner or a monthly invoice (as an aggregate expense) to all Owners. Each Owner shall pay each such invoice promptly upon, and in any event within thirty (30) days of, receipt of written notice thereof from the Common Facilities Manager. The Owners shall reimburse the Common Facilities Manager for Shared Expenses incurred by it in accordance with this Agreement. (b) As it becomes practicable and desirable, the Owners from time to time may designate additional expenses as Shared Expenses to be administered by the Common Facilities Manager in accordance with this Section 3.4 to the extent such additional expenses are similar to the other Shared Expenses. Notwithstanding the foregoing, no Owner shall be liable for any other Owner's Project expenses. (c) Except as otherwise provided in the Metering and Billing Agreement, any line losses occurring across the Common Physical Facilities and to the point of measurement at the Transmission Owner revenue meter at the Interconnection Point that cannot be specifically allocated to the operation of one Project (i.e., as when only one Project is operating) shall be allocated to the Owners pro rata in accordance with their then-applicable Proportionate Share. For purposes of clarity, the Parties agree that losses associated with any improvements which are not Common Physical Facilities will be the responsibility of the applicable Owner of those improvements. (d) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein (except as otherwise provided in this Agreement), all costs, expenses and/or liabilities (other than Shared Expenses) incurred by the Common Facilities Manager or either Owner that are attributed to the permitting, licensing, construction, initial start-up, testing and/or interconnection of a Project shall be the sole cost of such Project. Any monies paid by the Common Facilities Manager or any other Owner with respect to such items shall be promptly reimbursed by the applicable Owner. (e) Any agreement that is a Shared Project Agreement or a Shared Real Property Document or that otherwise results in Shared Expenses, in each case, entered into with an Affiliate of any Owner shall contain fees charged based on fair market value in a comparable arms' length transaction with an equally experienced Person not an Affiliate of an Owner. ARTICLE 4 COMMON FACILITIES MANAGEMENT 4.1 Common Facilities Manager. (a) Roosevelt shall be the initial "Common Facilities Manager" subject to its right to resign as Common Facilities Manager upon one hundred eighty (180) calendar days' notice to the Owners. If Roosevelt (or any other entity) resigns as Common Facilities Manager, the successor Common Facilities Manager shall be selected by the Owners Committee. In addition, either Owner may remove any Common Facilities Manager for (i) such Common Facilities Manager's material failure to comply with its obligations (under this Agreement or a separate Common Facilities management agreement, as applicable) within five (5) Business Days' notice and opportunity to cure (plus, in the case of a non-monetary default, such additional time as may be reasonably necessary provided cure is commenced within such five (5)-Business Day period and diligently and continuously prosecuted to completion), (ii) the Bankruptcy of Common Facilities Manager, or (iii) a sale, assignment, transfer or other disposition of the Common Facilities Manager's interest (if an Owner) in the Common Facilities or this Agreement that is not in accordance with the provisions of Article 8. If a Common Facilities Manager is removed pursuant to this Section 4.1(a), the successor Common Facilities Manager shall be selected by the Owners Committee. (b) The Common Facilities Manager shall serve for a term of twenty (20) years. No later than one hundred eighty (180) calendar days prior to the end of such term, the Owners Committee shall unanimously agree on the Common Facilities Manager for the next succeeding term. If the Common Facilities Manager is a third party, such party shall provide services pursuant to a contract satisfactory to the Owners Committee and consistent with (but not limited to) the requirements that would be applicable to the Common Facilities Manager pursuant to this Agreement if the Common Facilities Manager were one of the Owners. The foregoing shall apply with respect to each successive twenty (20) year period until this Agreement is terminated. 4.2 Powers and Duties of Common Facilities Manager. The Common Facilities Manager shall be authorized and obligated to do the following on behalf of each of the Owners; provided, however, that the Common Facilities Manager shall not be bound by a fiduciary duty to such Owners: (a) Operate and maintain the Common Facilities in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice, SPP Protocols, Applicable Laws and the Interconnection Agreement, and commercially reasonable terms included in any insurance policies covering the Common Facilities of which the Common Facilities Manager has received notice. The Common Facilities Manager either directly or through one or more subcontractors will provide for the operations and maintenance of the Common Facilities, including procurement of spare parts and such other services as may be desirable consistent with Prudent Industry Practice and Applicable Laws. In connection with any scheduled operation and maintenance, upon reasonable notice to the Owner(s) affected, the Common Facilities Manager is authorized to require each Owner, upon no less than five (5) Business Days' notice, to disconnect all or any portions of its Project, in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice, SPP Protocols and in compliance with the terms of this Agreement. The Common Facilities Manager shall coordinate with the Owner(s) affected to schedule the interruption, to the extent possible consistent with the standards set forth above, at a time least likely to adversely affect such Owners' projects, and to minimize the length of the interruption. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, the Common Facilities Manager shall operate and maintain the Common Facilities in a non-discriminatory manner, treating each Owner and its Project equally and fairly. (b) Subject to Section 5.7, prepare annual budgets for estimated Shared Expenses, inclusive of all expected third party costs and a reasonable estimation of the Common Facilities Manager's salaries, wages and overhead for the following year, and budget amendments as required with respect to the Common Facilities and present such budgets and budget amendments for review and approval by the Owners Committee (in the case of each annual budget, by no later than October 1 of the year prior to the year to which the budget relates); (c) Maintain books and records related to the Common Facilities in accordance with United States generally acceptable accounting principles and make such books and records available to each of the Owners upon the request of such Owner during the Common Facilities Manager's regular business hours; (d) Procure policies of insurance in accordance with Section 7.1; (e) Perform, in accordance with Prudent Industry Practice, such other duties as may be specified by the Owners Committee and agreed to by the Common Facilities Manager; (f) Execute such contracts and other documents as are necessary or appropriate to carry out the duties enumerated in Sections 4.2(a) through 4.2(e); (g) Submit statements to the Owners pursuant to Section 4.6 with respect to, and pay (to the extent of funds paid to it by the Owners pursuant to Section 4.7(a) or otherwise), bills and charges of third parties related to or in connection with the carrying out of the duties and obligations of the Common Facilities Manager pursuant to this Agreement; (h) Upon the request of any Owner, promptly provide to such Owner a statement, in such detail as may be reasonably requested by such Owner, of the amounts paid or payable or reimbursed or reimbursable by such Owner pursuant to Section 4.7; (i) Notify each Owner of (i) the assertion of any claim for bodily injury or property damage in excess of Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000) or greater related to the Common Facilities promptly following the Common Facilities Manager's knowledge of any such assertion and (ii) the Common Facilities Manager's knowledge of the occurrence of an event likely, in the reasonable determination of the Common Facilities Manager, to result in the assertion of such a claim promptly following any such occurrence. If any loss, damage or impairment to the Common Facilities occurs, the Common Facilities Manager shall apply the proceeds of any insurance policy with respect thereto to repair, replace or restore the Common Facilities to their prior condition if and to the extent permitted or required pursuant to the provisions of this Agreement; (j) Prepare, submit to each Owner for review and comment, and file in a timely manner any and all property tax returns required to be filed with respect to the Common Facilities; and include in budgets submitted to the Owners and pay in a timely manner any property tax owed in connection therewith, taking advantage of all available discounts for early payment (it being agreed, however, that each Owner shall have the right to protest any property tax assessment against the Common Facilities, and shall be entitled to recoup its costs in such contest to the extent they can be recouped out of tax savings achieved, whether in a single year or series of years); and (k) Except as permitted by this Agreement, the Common Facilities Manager shall not assign, subcontract or otherwise delegate its obligations hereunder other than to an Affiliate thereof which has sufficient skilled, knowledgeable and experienced personnel to perform the obligations of the Common Facilities Manager in accordance with the requirements of this Agreement or direct and manage the performance of such functions by the counterparty to any applicable Maintenance Agreement, without the consent of the Owners Committee. (l) Ad Valorem Taxes and Assessments. The Common Facilities Manager may seek from the applicable county tax assessor an allocation of ad valorem taxes of the Shared Premises and the Common Physical Facilities. If request is not made for an allocation of ad valorem taxes or the tax assessor fails to make such allocation, the Common Facilities Manager shall make such allocation based upon the actual cost of such Common Physical Facilities (including installation thereof) and value of the Shared Premises. 4.3 Limitations on Common Facilities Manager's Rights. Notwithstanding Section 4.2 above, following the Effective Date the Common Facilities Manager shall not be permitted to do or take any of the following actions without the express prior written consent of the Owners Committee: (a) Disposition of Assets. Selling, leasing, pledging, mortgaging, conveying, licensing, exchanging or otherwise transferring or disposing of any material property or assets comprising the Common Facilities except in the ordinary course in instances where any disposed items are being repaired or replaced; (b) Contracts. Executing, amending, modifying, terminating or supplementing any Shared Project Agreement, Shared License and Permit or Shared Real Property Document in a manner that materially and adversely affects an Owner; (c) Borrowing. Borrowing any money on behalf of or in the name of the Owners, utilizing the Owners' property as security for any loans, obligating the Owners as guarantors, endorsers, sureties or accommodation parties, or otherwise pledging the credit of the Owners in any way other than the incurring of trade accounts in the ordinary course of business (provided, however, nothing in this clause shall be deemed to prevent or prohibit any Owner from borrowing funds, issuing guarantees, or encumbering its assets, including its Proportionate Share, in connection with any corporate financing or any project financing of such Owner's Project); (d) Loans. Lending any money, or extending any credit, on behalf of or in the name of the Owners; (e) Affiliate Contracts. Executing, amending, modifying, terminating or supplementing any agreements with Affiliates of the Common Facilities Manager on behalf of the Owners; (f) Lawsuits and Settlements. Settling, compromising, assigning, pledging, transferring, releasing or consenting to do the same, any claim, suit, debt, demand or judgment against, or due or by the Owners or the Common Facilities Manager on behalf of the Owners, submitting any such claim, dispute or controversy to arbitration or judicial process, or stipulation thereof to a judgment, or consent to do the same to the extent that any of the foregoing relate to an amount in controversy in excess of $1,000,000 or the amount covered by applicable insurance proceeds; (g) Expenditures. Making any expenditure on behalf of the Owners for any equipment, materials, assets or other items or services, or making any capital or other non-recurring expenditure, or consenting or agreeing to do any of the foregoing unless otherwise contemplated in the Shared Project Agreements or contemplated in the then applicable annual budget proposed by the Common Facilities Manager and approved in writing by the Owners, provided, however, that the Common Facilities Manager may make reasonable expenditures beyond the applicable annual budget to respond to an emergency and/or to comply with Applicable Laws; or (h) Governing Authority. Taking any action contradictory to an express directive or instruction given by the Owners, so long as such directive or instruction does not violate or breach any Applicable Laws, Shared Project Agreements, Shared Real Property Documents, Shared Licenses and Permits or this Agreement. 4.4 Removal of Common Facilities Manager. The Common Facilities Manager may be removed (a) pursuant to Sections 4.1(a) or 9.6(b), or (b) for cause by any Owner; provided that each of the following conditions are satisfied: (i) the Common Facilities Manager has defaulted in its material obligations under this Agreement; (ii) the Owner seeking removal of the Common Facilities Manager for cause has provided written notice to the Common Facilities Manager and the other Owners of such default by the Common Facilities Manager hereunder, which notice shall contain a general description of the facts and circumstances giving rise to such default; and (iii) the Common Facilities Manager has failed to cure such default described in the notice within thirty (30) days after delivery of such written notice; provided that, if such default is not reasonably capable of being cured within thirty (30) days, then the Common Facilities Manager shall have an additional period of time, but in no event more than ninety (90) days from the delivery of such written notice to cure such default. No removal of the Common Facilities Manager shall be effective unless and until a successor Common Facilities Manager is appointed by the Owners (such successor however may not be the person or company that has been acting as the removed Common Facilities Manager); provided, however, that notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein, if the Common Facilities Manager is removed pursuant to Section 9.6(b), then the other Owners shall select the Common Facilities Manager. Notwithstanding anything herein to the contrary contained herein, no removal of an Owner as the Common Facilities Manager shall affect such Owner's rights as an Owner, and no default by an Owner as the Common Facilities Manager shall constitute a default by that Owner in its capacity as an Owner. 4.5 Step-in Rights. (a) If the Common Facilities Manager defaults in its material obligations under this Agreement or fails to perform any of its material obligations under this Agreement, in each case, after the receipt of a written notice from an Owner identifying such breach or non-performance and the expiration of a thirty (30) day cure period (which cure period may be extended for up to ninety (90) days if the breach or non-performance cannot reasonably be cured within such thirty (30) day period and the Common Facilities Manager is otherwise exercising commercially reasonable efforts to effectuate a cure or remedy such non-performance), then such Owner shall have the right to step-in and effectuate such cure or perform on behalf of the Common Facilities Manager after the expiration of the relevant cure period (or to cause a third party to step-in and effectuate such cure or perform such task). (b) Each Owner shall additionally have a license, on behalf of the Common Facilities Manager and the other Owners, to enter onto the property covered by the Shared Real Property Documents or other underlying real property interests to: (i) inspect any wind power facilities constructed or maintained thereon, including, but not limited to, the Common Physical Facilities, (ii) promptly implement, supervise, monitor, organize and undertake activities necessary to deal with emergency situations affecting the Common Physical Facilities involving risks to person or property or interfering with the normal operation of the Common Physical Facilities or the Projects if the Common Facilities Manager is unable to resolve such issues on an emergency basis such items have not been remedied by the Common Facilities Manager, (iii) perform or install necessary or beneficial repairs and/or upgrades to the Common Physical Facilities which the Common Facilities Manager has failed to implement or undertake the following five (5) Business Days prior written notice from such Owner, and (iv) cure any breaches or defaults existing with respect to the Shared Real Property Documents. 4.6 Authorized Expenditures. To the extent included in an annual budget or a budget amendment approved and effective pursuant to Sections 5.7 through 5.9 of this Agreement, each of the Owners shall reimburse to the Common Facilities Manager its Proportionate Share of (i) the salaries, wages and related indirect and reasonable overhead costs for the Common Facilities Manager's personnel who perform the duties and obligations of the Common Facilities Manager pursuant to this Agreement and (ii) the reasonable payments by the Common Facilities Manager to third parties related to or in connection with the carrying out of the duties and obligations of the Common Facilities Manager pursuant to this Agreement. The Common Facilities Manager will not be entitled to recovery with respect to any costs or payments (including, pursuant to any judgment, decree, injunction, Order or decision by any Governmental Authority) incurred or owing by the Common Facilities Manager as a result of or in connection with any mistake, action, inaction or omission constituting gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct by the Common Facilities Manager. 4.7 Reimbursement of Approved Costs. (a) Funds to pay for amounts expended pursuant to Section 4.6 with respect to the Common Facilities shall be paid by each Owner at the beginning of each calendar month in accordance with the then applicable annual budget. Not later than five (5) Business Days prior to the start of each calendar month (or such other billing period as is agreed by the Owners), the Common Facilities Manager shall deliver to each Owner a statement and accounting showing the computation in reasonable detail of the amount to be advanced to the account to pay for such expenditures, which shall be within budgeted figures for the coming month adjusted for any surplus funds or funding inadequacies carried over from the latest completed month as accounted for in such statement and accounting. The Common Facilities Manager shall furnish any receipts, documents, and other information in connection with each such statement as may reasonably show the basis for individual billings, charges, and cost computations, up to the date of such statement. The Common Facilities Manager shall promptly provide to each Owner such receipts, documents and other information in connection with each such statement as such Owner may reasonably request. Within thirty (30) calendar days after receipt of each such statement, each Owner shall make a report in writing to the Common Facilities Manager of any dispute concerning such statement. Each Owner shall pay to the Common Facilities Manager any amount undisputed by such Owner set forth in such statement within ten (10) Business Days. Any dispute concerning a statement shall be subject to the dispute resolution process set forth in Section 10.1. Such payment shall be made by each Owner to the Common Facilities Manager in immediately available funds by electronic wire transfer, or by deposit otherwise made within ten (10) Business Days after resolution of the dispute, into the account designated in writing from time to time by the Common Facilities Manager for such purpose. (b) The Common Facilities Manager shall make available during regular business hours, for inspection and audit by each of the Owners, all books and records of the Common Facilities Manager evidencing the amounts contained in each statement and accounting provided to such Owner pursuant to Section 4.7(a). Such books and records shall be retained by the Common Facilities Manager for such period as the Owners Committee may determine, but not less than one (1) year; and such books and records shall be made available by the Common Facilities Manager for inspection and audit by each of the Owners during the Common Facilities Manager's regular business hours. The costs and expenses of any inspection or audit requested by an Owner shall be borne by the Owner requesting such inspection or audit. (c) The Common Facilities Manager also shall permit any Owner to inspect the Common Facilities during regular business hours, provided that such Owner provides at least one Business Days' notice of such inspection and complies with the safety requirements imposed by the Common Facilities Manager on all visitors. 4.8 NERC and Regional Entity Requirements. (a) In the event that the Owners or a Governmental Authority determines that the Common Facilities operate in a manner or perform functions which require that their Owners and operator register with NERC or the Regional Entity, (i) the Common Facilities Manager shall serve as the Transmission Owner and/or Transmission Operator of the Common Facilities and (ii) all third-party costs and expenses, fees, losses, damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens and penalties, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys' and consultants' fees, related to, associated with or in connection with fulfilling the requirements under the NERC and Regional Entity standards that are applicable to the Transmission Owner and/or Transmission Operator for the Common Facilities and the Owners' operation and maintenance of the Common Facilities in connection therewith ("TO/TOP Expenses") shall be apportioned between the Owners in accordance with its Proportionate Share. (b) Each Owner shall be solely responsible for any TO/TOP Expenses (including, without limitation, fines and/or penalties) caused by such Owners' breach of this Agreement. In the event that the Common Facilities are jurisdictional transmission assets which, as reasonably determined by the Owners, require the Owners to register with NERC or the Regional Entity as a Transmission Owner and/or Transmission Operator, the Owners shall not take any action in violation of any NERC or Regional Entity requirements. (c) Owners and the Common Facilities Manager shall not take any action, or refrain from taking any action, to intentionally cause the Common Physical Facilities to be subjected to the NERC or Regional Entity compliance requirements described above in Sections 4.8(a) and (b). ARTICLE 5 OWNERS COMMITTEE 5.1 Establishment of Committee; Voting. There is hereby established an "Owners Committee" for the Owners to take all actions which have not been expressly delegated to the Common Facilities Manager pursuant to Article 4, except as otherwise provided in Section 5.8, and to take all other actions that all of the Owners may, from time to time, agree in writing that the Owners Committee is authorized to take in connection with the ownership (as applicable), construction, rebuilding, operation, maintenance, repair, replacement and removal of the Common Facilities, or any portion thereof. Each Owner shall have a representative on the Owners Committee. Each decision by the Owners Committee must be unanimous. Each Owner shall have the right to cast one vote with respect to any decision, approval or other action to be made by the Owners Committee. If an Owner is entitled to vote on the matter presented to the Owners Committee and is participating in a meeting of the Owners Committee but does not vote either in favor of or against any matter subject to a decision, approval or other action of the Owners Committee pursuant to this Agreement, such Owner shall be deemed to have voted against it. A matter shall be deemed approved by the Owners Committee only if it shall have been approved by all of the votes of the Owners regardless of whether such Owners or their representative members on the Owners Committee are in attendance at the meeting. 5.2 Appointment of Members; Alternates. The initial number of members of the Owners Committee shall be two (2) representing Roosevelt and Milo. Each Owner shall be entitled to appoint one (1) member to the Owners Committee, which appointment shall be deemed effective upon notice to the other Owners. Any Owner (or its successors and assigns, acting collectively) may change its Owners Committee member(s) by giving notice of such changes to each other Owner. Any Owner (or its successors and assigns, acting collectively), by giving notice to each other Owner, may, for purposes of any decision, approval or other action to be made by the Owners Committee pursuant to this Agreement, appoint an alternate or alternates to serve on the Owners Committee in the place of, and to cast the vote of, the regular Owners Committee member appointed by such Owner. 5.3 Meetings. The Owners Committee shall meet at such time and place as may be agreed upon by the members of the Owners Committee and the Owners Committee shall meet at such other times and places as may be requested by any Owners Committee member by notice to each other Owners Committee member at least ten (10) calendar days prior to such meeting. Members of the Owners Committee may participate in such meetings in person or by means of conference telephone calls or similar communications during which all persons participating in the meeting can hear each other. Participation in a meeting by means of conference telephone calls or similar communications shall be deemed to constitute presence in person at the meeting. No actions or decisions of the Owners Committee may be taken or made at any meeting without all of the Owners Committee members being present. 5.4 Decisions by Written Action. Any decisions, approvals and other actions that may be taken at a meeting of the Owners Committee may be taken without a meeting if all Owners Committee members consent thereto in writing. The Owners Committee may, by the unanimous vote of the members of the Owners Committee, adopt procedures for review or approval of matters or for the taking of other actions concerning the Common Facilities. 5.5 Subcommittees. The Owners Committee may appoint such subcommittees as it deems necessary or appropriate and, by the unanimous vote of all of the members of the Owners Committee, may delegate approval authority to such subcommittees with respect to matters concerning the Common Facilities. Members of a subcommittee are not required to otherwise be a member of the Owners Committee. 5.6 Major Decisions. Notwithstanding anything in this Agreement to the contrary, the following shall require the unanimous approval of the Owners Committee: (a) approval or amendment of the annual budgets and budget amendments prepared by the Common Facilities Manager pursuant to Section 4.2(b); (b) approval of contracts or commitments involving or expected to involve aggregate expenditures of more than $50,000.00 for expenses within a budget approved by the Owners Committee (or otherwise in effect pursuant to Section 5.7); (c) approval of the incurrence of costs, with respect to any line item in a budget approved by the Owners Committee (or otherwise in effect pursuant to Section 5.7) in excess of such line item budget; (d) approval of the incurrence of aggregate costs for any calendar year in excess of the total budgeted costs for such year as set forth in a budget approved by the Owners Committee (or otherwise in effect pursuant to Section 5.7); (e) any decision to remove from service permanently or otherwise to sell, transfer, assign or dispose of all or any part of the Common Facilities; and (f) any decision to incur or to authorize the Common Facilities Manager to incur any indebtedness related to the Common Facilities that the Owners would be obligated to repay pursuant to this Agreement, other than a Lender's Lien against an individual Owner's Proportionate Share incurred in accordance with Section 8.1(c). 5.7 Budgets. If for any reason the Owners Committee does not approve an annual budget prior to the end of the eleventh (11th) month of the preceding calendar year (other than the budget applicable during the first year), the budget for such preceding year shall apply to the current year, subject to an increase or decrease in such budget to reflect the change in the GDPIPD for all goods and services during the twelve (12)-month period ending with the tenth (10th) month of such preceding year. 5.8 Emergency Actions. The Common Facilities Manager (or any Owner, if Common Facilities Manager is unavailable or fails to act) shall have the right but not the duty to proceed with an item that has not been approved (even if it has been disapproved) as provided in this Article 5, if the Common Facilities Manager (or any Owner, if Common Facilities Manager is unavailable or fails to act) determines in its reasonable judgment that such action is required to avoid an imminent threat of loss of life or property or is required to avoid an imminent threat of interruption of service to the Owner of a Project; provided, however, that Common Facilities Manager (or any Owner, if Common Facilities Manager is unavailable or fails to act) must give notice of such action to each Owner as soon as reasonably possible and further provided that if the Common Facilities Manager (or any Owner) takes such action on a disapproved item and if the determination made in any subsequent review of the decision is that the item was not consistent with Prudent Industry Practice, then the Common Facilities Manager (or such Owner) shall not be entitled to reimbursement for any of the cost or expense of such action. 5.9 Tax Election. Each of the Owners shall, to the extent permitted by Section 761 of the Code, elect as provided in Treasury Regulation Section 1.761-2 to exclude from the provisions of Subchapter K of the Code any organization that they may otherwise comprise by virtue of this Agreement. 5.10 Deadlocks. If the Owners Committee reaches deadlock on an issue, such that the Owners fall short of unanimity (a "Deadlock"), and any Party gives written notice to the other(s) that such has occurred, then the Owners will use all reasonable efforts to reach a satisfactory solution by referring the Deadlock to senior management of each of the Owners or their parent entities. In the event that a Deadlock has been declared, senior management of the Owners or their parent entities will meet as soon as possible, on no less than five (5) Business Days' notice, unless specifically agreed otherwise. Any Deadlock that cannot be resolved by further negotiations by such senior management shall be determined as set forth in Article 10. ARTICLE 6 COVENANTS 6.1 Covenants of the Owners. The Owners hereby covenant as follows: (a) Mechanic's Liens. Each Owner shall not permit any mechanic's liens arising out of its use of the Common Facilities pursuant to this Agreement to exist against the Common Facilities. If an Owner wishes to contest any such lien, that Owner shall, within sixty (60) calendar days after it receives notice of the lien, provide a bond or other security to the other Owners as those other Owners may reasonably request, or remove such lien from the affected property pursuant to Applicable Law. (b) Environmental Laws. Each Owner shall comply with Environmental Laws in connection with its separate activities of its Project and Common Facilities. Each Owner agrees to indemnify the other Owners and the Common Facilities Manager against such Owner's violation of the Environmental Laws on its Project and Common Facilities, including such violations by its agents or contractors. The foregoing indemnities shall not apply to the extent of any gross negligence or willful misconduct by the Party being indemnified, or to any acts or omissions of the Common Facilities Manager conducted with respect to the Common Facilities in accordance with this Agreement and approved by the Owners Committee. (c) [Reserved] (d) Taxes. Subject to Section 4.2(j), each Owner shall pay, when due, all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its facilities and/or operations subject to such Party's right to contest by appropriate legal proceedings the validity or applicability of any such taxes and assessments; provided that no such contest shall be permitted if it would expose the Common Facilities to a risk of loss by forfeiture or otherwise. (e) Compliance with Law. Each Owner shall, at its sole cost and expense, promptly comply with all Applicable Laws and with all covenants, conditions and restrictions in effect regulating the use of the Common Facilities or any facilities owned by such Owner thereon until this Agreement is terminated; provided however, that such Owner shall have the right to contest by appropriate legal proceedings and in its own name the validity or applicability of any such Applicable Law; provided that no such contest shall be permitted if it would expose the Common Facilities to a risk of loss by forfeiture or otherwise. (f) Conduct of Activities. Each Owner shall (i) conduct its operations and activities of its Project and the Common Facilities in accordance with all Applicable Laws and Prudent Industry Practices, and (ii) to the extent necessary to avoid a material adverse effect with respect to the condition or operation of the Common Facilities or an increase in insurance premiums with respect thereto, keep its facilities in good condition and repair, in good and efficient working order and in a safe condition. Neither any Owner nor the Common Facilities Manager shall conduct its operations or activities, or use or permit the use of the Common Facilities or any part thereof or its facilities in any manner that will cause physical damage to the Common Facilities or any part thereof, or cause an increase in insurance premiums with respect thereto and each Owner (and the Common Facilities Manager, if not an Owner) shall be responsible for any such physical damage (but shall not incur any liability for any down-time resulting from any operations or activities conducted in accordance with Applicable Laws, Prudent Industry Practices and otherwise in accordance with this Agreement). Each Owner shall exercise reasonable efforts to coordinate with the other Owners in the timing and duration of maintenance to the transmission lines on the Common Facilities and the other portions of the Owners' Projects (to the extent maintenance of such Projects would materially impair the use by the other Owners of the Common Facilities or the transmission lines on such Common Facilities); provided however, that if the Owners cannot agree to the timing and duration of any such maintenance, any dispute shall be subject to the dispute resolution process set forth in Section 10.1; provided further, however, that each Owner shall have the right to perform any maintenance required in the case of any action which it determines in its reasonable judgment is required to avoid an imminent threat of loss of life or property or is required to avoid an imminent threat of interruption of service to the Owner in accordance with the process set forth in Section 5.8. (g) Confidentiality of Owner Information. Each Owner agrees to maintain the confidentiality of the Information, except that Information may be disclosed (a) to its Affiliates, managers, partners, directors, officers, employees, advisors, agents, consultants, lenders, and potential lenders, investors and purchasers to or of an Owner or any of its Affiliates (and their respective advisors, consultants and counsel); it being understood that the Persons to whom such disclosure is made will be informed of the confidential nature of such Information and, other than with respect to a ratings agency, required to keep such Information confidential pursuant to a confidentiality agreement similar in nature to this Section 6.1(g) or be under a duty to keep such Information confidential that is at least as restrictive as the confidentiality obligations set forth in this Section 6.1(g), (b) to the extent requested by any regulatory authority having jurisdiction over the Owners, (c) to the extent required by Applicable Laws or regulations or by any subpoena or similar legal process, (d) in any legal action or proceeding relating to this Agreement or the Common Facilities, or (e) to the extent such Information (i) becomes publicly available other than as a result of a breach of this Section or (ii) becomes available to any Owner on a non-confidential basis from a source other than the Owner to whom such Information relates. For purposes of this Agreement, "Information" means all information received pursuant to this Agreement or during the design, use or operation of the Common Facilities from an Owner or relating to an Owner or any of the Projects or businesses, other than any such information that is available to any Owner on a non-confidential basis prior to disclosure by the Owner to whom such Information relates. ARTICLE 7 INSURANCE 7.1 Insurance for Common Facilities. Each Owner shall, at its expense, maintain a commercial general liability insurance policy insuring it and the other Owner and the Common Facilities Manager against loss or liability caused by such Owner's use of the Common Facilities and the land on which they are located, in an amount not less than Five Million Dollars ($5,000,000) of combined single limit liability coverage per occurrence, accident or incident, which has a commercially reasonable deductible. Each Owner shall, at its expense, maintain a policy of casualty insurance covering the Common Facilities in an amount equal to the full replacement cost thereof. Certificates of such insurance evidencing the coverages required by this Agreement shall be provided to the other Owners upon reasonable request. Each Owner shall have the right to use a qualified program of self-insurance to meet the insurance requirements, and may also provide any such insurance pursuant to one or more blanket insurance policies maintained by such Party or its Affiliates. ARTICLE 8 TRANSFER OF INTERESTS; LIENS 8.1 Restrictions on Transfer. No Owner shall sell, assign or otherwise transfer any of its ownership interest or other rights or interests in or to the Common Facilities, or in, to or under this Agreement, without (i) assigning or transferring such Common Facilities and Agreement rights and interests together to the same assignee(s), such that the Common Facilities are not separated in ownership from the rights and interests under this Agreement (provided, however, that the Owners may apportion their interest in the Common Facilities and their rights and obligations under this Agreement to multiple separate transferees that are successor owners of one or more of the Projects, or desire to build one or more Projects with portions of such interests), and (ii) obtaining the prior written consent of the other Owner, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed by such other Owner, except that such consent shall not be required for a sale, assignment or transfer by an Owner (a "Transferring Party") in the following circumstances: (a) the assignee or transferee is an entity with which the Transferring Party has consolidated or into which the Transferring Party has merged or which acquires by conveyance, transfer or lease all or substantially all of the assets of such Transferring Party and such purchaser, assignee, lessee or assignee shall have agreed in writing to assume all of the future obligations of such Transferring Party under this Agreement; or (b) the assignee or transferee owns (or will own upon the transfer) an appropriate equivalent ownership interest in the Project(s) owned by the Transferring Party which produce electricity transmitted over the lines supported by the Common Facilities; or (c) a transfer in the nature of a lien, security interest or collateral assignment (each a "Lender's Lien") as security for a debt, equity or obligation to a third party (a "Lender"), or the foreclosure (or conveyance or assignment in lieu of foreclosure) of such Lender's Lien), provided that, in the case of foreclosure of a Lender's Lien, the requirements of (b) above are also met; provided, however, that no such assignment or a foreclosure on such assignment shall subordinate or otherwise adversely affect the rights of the other Owners in and to this Agreement or the Common Facilities covered hereby. The restrictions on transfer contained in this Section 8.1 shall not apply with respect to transfers of equity ownership in an Owner itself, or in connection with the transfer of assets, or equity interests in any entity, in either case owned by an owner, member, shareholder, or other Person owning an equity interest (directly or indirectly) in an Owner. 8.2 Surrender and Assignment of Proportionate Share .
